<Review ID>2969988
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Black
<Title>Only 3 stars because of certain malfunctions.
<Date>Fri Mar 10 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>My boyfriend bought 2 of these, one for him and myself.  After three months, I did not have a single problem.  However, his developed a firmware problem last week, deleted all of his files (including those from CDs he lost), and refused to be updated.  He called tech support, but before he mailed it in, the problem resolved itself and he was able to update the firmware (but unfortunately did not recover his files).    Now today, when he turned it on, the headphone jack loosened up, and the sound cut in and out.  He called tech support yet again, got the RMA number, and will mail it out next week.  Again, I haven't had a single problem with mine.  They're the same exact player, color, and battery, and mine takes more abuse because I use it as a 1 GB partitioned flash drive.  It has fallen on the floor a number of times and only received a small scratch on the screen.  This is my first experience with a hard drive-based mp3 player, since up to this point I was using a Creative MuVo Nomad (flash drive based).    I think it depends on a person's luck with products like these.  If you've never had a problem with electronics malfunctioning, there's a good chance you'll love this player.  Final note:  BUY THE CREATIVE PROTECTION PLAN with this player.  And keep your receipt.  Just in case.  
<Overall>3

<Review ID>2712911
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Black
<Title>A Good Music Player
<Date>Tue Sep 26 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>Though outdated now in terms of space, functionality and cost...this player has worked perfectly for me. It's Screen interface is easy to use, even with the clumsy hands I've got and it still has enough weight in it to make it blindly useable (ie. picking it up while doing something else like driving and changing songs without ever having to look at it). I'd maybe guess that Apple's iPOD Nano could do the same thing, but as little as it weighs, I'd be afraid a gust of wind might blow it away, lol. In fact, it's jsut perfect size for me to switch albums while I'm riding a bike, but you should REALLY practice a LOT if you're gonna try that lil' trick....don't say I didn't warn you! It survived a 19 inch fall to concrete with no problems....but I might've been lucky. 'Sides since I'm a mostly happy user of Windows Computers, it didn't make sense to buy something that doesn't support Outlook. The radio recieves "decently" and the voice recorder is swell too. Sound quality is good to me, but I'm not very picky on that subject so someone used to more might be disappointed. My only gripe is I couldn't find the color I wanted at Wal-Mart...Orange would've been interesting:) Battery life is decent, but like most other players I've had it seems to require the light off and minimal changing of albums and the like. I average 5 hours myself.   
<Overall>5

